4","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Skotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1344–1390":"1344–1390","1324–1344":"1324–1344","1344–Female":"1344–Overleden","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1296–1344":"1296–1344","1294–1346":"1294–1346","1425":"1425","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1344":"1344","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Schotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1344–1390":"1344–1390","1324–1344":"1324–1344","1344–Female":"1344–Deceased","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1296–1344":"1296–1344","1294–1346":"1294–1346","1425":"1425","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1344":"1344","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Scotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Barton was born in 1344, in St Monans, Fife, Scotland, his father, Sir. Thomas Barton, was 48 and his mother, Lady Beatrix Burdett, was 50. He married Margaret de Barton in 1390, in St Monans, Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1390, in Otterburn, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1344–1390":"1344–1390","1324–1344":"1324–1344","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1296–1344":"1296–1344","1294–1346":"1294–1346","1425":"1425","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1344":"1344","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Scotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1344–1390":"1344–1390","1324–1344":"1324–1344","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1390–1425"